<p><strong>Premium Burgundian Pinot Noir</strong> (Gevrey-Chambertin, Chassagne-Montrachet) develops beautifully over 8-15 years, with Grand Cru bottlings aging gracefully for 20+ years. <strong>Barolo and Brunello di Montalcino</strong> require patience—these DOCG wines need 10-12 years minimum to soften their formidable tannins, with exceptional vintages evolving for three decades.</p>

<p><strong>Champagne and premium sparkling wines</strong> present unique considerations. Vintage Champagnes peak at 10-15 years, developing honeyed complexity and brioche notes, while prestige cuvées like Dom Pérignon can age magnificently for 20+ years. Non-vintage Champagnes should be consumed within 3-5 years of purchase.</p>

