<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine goes best with both turkey and ham at Christmas dinner?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Pinot Noir is the ideal bridge wine for Christmas dinners featuring both turkey and ham, as its medium body and bright acidity complement poultry while its subtle earthiness pairs beautifully with glazed ham. A Burgundian-style Pinot Noir from Oregon's Willamette Valley or California's Russian River Valley offers enough complexity to handle both proteins without overwhelming either. The wine's natural cherry and spice notes also echo traditional Christmas flavors like cranberry sauce and warming spices.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve red or white wine with Christmas dinner's heavy sides like stuffing and gravy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rich, full-bodied red wines work best with heavy Christmas sides because their tannins cut through the fat in gravy and their robust flavors stand up to herb-heavy stuffing. Côtes du Rhône, Zinfandel, or a medium-bodied Cabernet Sauvignon provide enough structure to complement these indulgent dishes. However, if serving lighter sides like roasted vegetables, a full-bodied white wine like aged Chardonnay or white Rhône blend can also work well.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How many bottles of wine should I buy for a Christmas dinner party of 8 people?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Plan for 4-5 bottles of wine for 8 guests at Christmas dinner, assuming a 4-hour celebration with appetizers, dinner, and dessert. This accounts for approximately half a bottle per person, which is standard for a festive meal with multiple courses. Consider having 2-3 bottles of red wine (your primary dinner wines), 1-2 bottles of white or sparkling for appetizers and lighter palates, and keep one extra bottle on hand for unexpected guests or enthusiastic wine lovers.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when choosing Christmas dinner wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is choosing wines that are too heavy or tannic for the festive atmosphere, such as big Cabernet Sauvignon or Barolo, which can overwhelm traditional Christmas flavors and clash with sweet elements like cranberry sauce or glazed vegetables. Instead, opt for food-friendly wines with balanced acidity and moderate tannins that complement rather than compete with your meal. Remember that Christmas dinner often includes sweeter components that need wines with enough fruit character to harmonize rather than fight.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good budget-friendly wines under $20 that work for Christmas dinner?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely - many excellent Christmas dinner wines can be found under $20, including Washington State Merlot, Portuguese Douro reds, and Spanish Garnacha blends that offer great value and food-pairing versatility. Look for wines from regions like Languedoc in France or Central Coast California, which produce high-quality, approachable wines perfect for holiday meals. Côtes du Rhône villages wines and Oregon Pinot Gris also provide excellent quality-to-price ratios for Christmas entertaining.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">When should I open red wine before serving it at Christmas dinner?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Open red wines 30-60 minutes before serving Christmas dinner to allow them to breathe and reach optimal serving temperature (60-65°F). Younger, more tannic reds like Cabernet Sauvignon benefit from longer breathing time (up to 90 minutes), while lighter reds like Pinot Noir need only 15-30 minutes. If you're serving multiple wines throughout the meal, stagger your opening times so each wine is perfectly ready when needed.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine alternatives work for guests who don't drink alcohol at Christmas dinner?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sparkling grape juice, cranberry juice cocktails, and alcohol-free wine alternatives like Ariel or Fre provide festive options that mirror the wine experience without alcohol. For a more sophisticated approach, serve sparkling apple cider or pomegranate juice mixed with sparkling water in wine glasses to maintain the celebratory feel. These alternatives can be paired with the same food considerations as wine - lighter options with appetizers and richer alternatives with the main course.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I pair wine with Christmas desserts, or should I switch to something else?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Traditional Christmas desserts pair beautifully with dessert wines - try Port with chocolate yule log, Moscato d'Asti with fruit-based desserts, or late-harvest Riesling with apple pie or Christmas cookies. For lighter desserts, a glass of Champagne or Prosecco cleanses the palate perfectly. If your guests prefer, coffee, tea, or digestifs like brandy or liqueurs also make excellent post-dinner beverages that complement the holiday spirit.</p>
  </div>
